##City at rest? How many people are on the road

Article: Sun Yu, He Miao Editor: Chen Chen Chen

"Most cities should no longer remain 'static, ' " said a commentary in the Global Times on Feb. 17, "We should laugh at the fact that the streets of a big city of ten million people are empty because of the very few cases that are tracked every day, and break it, " he said, how many people are going out in different cities in the first week back to work?

On road traffic, our reporter selected 16 cities, including Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Tianjin, Chongqing, Hangzhou, Nanjing, Chengdu, Shenyang, Changsha, Xi'an, Zhengzhou, Suzhou, Ningbo, Qingdao, etc. , the peak congestion index of cities in Baidu smart map from February 10 to 15 was compared with the peak congestion index of commuting in cities in the first quarter of 2019 to see the extent of urban road traffic congestion.

Among first-tier cities, Beijing's congestion index last week fell the most from its level in the first quarter of last year, with an average drop of 42.93 per cent over five working days. Shenzhen saw the smallest drop, with its five-day congestion index down 31.97 per cent on average from the first quarter of last year.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Of the other 14 cities, Chongqing saw the biggest drop. In the first quarter of last year, Chongqing was the most congested city in the country, with a commuter congestion index of 2.251, according to Baidu maps. Last week, the peak congestion index in Chongqing fluctuated between 1.03 and 1.04 on weekdays, with an average drop of 54.15 percent on five days.

Compared with the first quarter of last year, the smallest decline in the fourteen cities is Ningbo. Ningbo fell an average of 22.39 per cent in the five working days last week.

During the epidemic prevention and control period, many cities across the country have implemented road traffic control measures, suspended road public transport (such as Hangzhou) or reduced passenger trips. At the same time, Beijing, Tianjin and other cities suspended the implementation of vehicle tail number restrictions to encourage private cars to travel.

Regarding Urban Rail Transit, according to public information, the interface data reporter compared the intensity of subway passenger flow in the above-mentioned 16 cities on February 10-15 with the intensity of passenger flow on the same day in the lunar calendar last year. The results show that the average passenger flow intensity in 16 cities decreased by 93.69% .

The intensity of subway passenger flow in the four first-tier cities has dropped by about 90% . The biggest drop was in Shenzhen, where the intensity of passenger flow on the six days between January 17 and twenty-two was 92.95% lower than the same period last year, and Beijing, where the intensity of passenger flow also dropped by more than 90% to 92.87% .

Outside the four first-tier cities, the other 14 cities that the interface data reporter counted last week saw an average drop of more than 90 percent in passenger flow intensity. The biggest drop was in Xi'an, where passenger flow dropped 96.68 percent last week compared with the same period last year. In Qingdao, where the drop was the smallest, passenger flow on the metro dropped 91.51 percent from the same period last year.

Similar to road traffic control, rail traffic control measures were introduced in several cities during the epidemic. For example, Ningbo has suspended rail transit operations since February 6 and only gradually resumed operations on February 15. On Feb. 15, the intensity of passenger flow on the Ningbo subway dropped by 93.62 percent compared with the same period last year. Shanghai, Tianjin and other cities in the Spring Festival period to stop some sections or close some stations way. In addition, Beijing, Guangzhou and other cities have also introduced measures to strictly control the subway full load rate.

There are many reasons for the decrease of urban road and rail traffic flow. On the one hand, many cities have introduced isolation or closed management policies, adding traffic restrictions, reducing the amount of travel by urban residents.

On the other hand, there is still a large number of floating population has not returned to the city, the total urban population is lower than the same period in previous years. The Ministry of Transport of the People's Republic of China revealed at a press conference held by the Guoxin Administration on February 15 that as of February 14,283 million passenger trips had been sent across the country after the holiday (January 25 to February 14) , an average of 13.48 million passenger trips per day, down 82.3 percent from the same period last year, only one-sixth of the passenger flow during the Spring Festival travel season. It is estimated that migrant workers will make about 120 million return trips by the end of February, more than 100 million return trips after March, and about 100 million return trips for students waiting to return to school.

Recently, a number of provinces such as Fujian, Hainan, Zhejiang, Anhui and Jiangxi have introduced differentiated prevention and control policies of "grading and zoning" . With better outbreak data and more accurate prevention and control, more people will be on the roads.
